# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: xen-hypervisor
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] A **hypervisor**, also known as a **virtual machine monitor** (**VMM**), is a type of computer software, firmware or hardware that creates and runs virtual machines.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] A computer on which a hypervisor runs one or more virtual machines is called a *host machine* or *virtualization server*, and each virtual machine is called a *guest machine*.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] The hypervisor presents the guest operating systems with a virtual operating platform and manages the execution of the guest operating systems.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Unlike an emulator, the guest executes most instructions on the native hardware.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Multiple instances of a variety of operating systems may share the virtualized hardware resources: for example, Linux, Windows, and macOS instances can all run on a single physical x86 machine.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] This contrasts with operating system-level virtualization, where all instances (usually called *containers*) must share a single kernel, though the guest operating systems can differ in user space, such as different Linux distributions with the same kernel.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] The term *hypervisor* is a variant of *supervisor*, a traditional term for the kernel of an operating system: the hypervisor is the supervisor of the supervisors, with *hyper-* used as a stronger variant of *super-*.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] The term dates to circa 1970; IBM coined it for software that ran OS/360 and the 7090 emulator concurrently on the 360/65 and later used it for the DIAG handler of CP-67.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] In the earlier CP/CMS (1967) system, the term *Control Program* was used instead.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Some literature, especially in microkernel contexts, makes a distinction between *hypervisor* and *virtual machine monitor* (*VMM*).
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] There, both components form the overall *virtualization stack* of a certain system.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] *Hypervisor* refers to kernel-space functionality and VMM to user-space functionality.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Specifically in these contexts, a *hypervisor* is a microkernel implementing virtualization infrastructure that must run in kernel-space for technical reasons, such as Intel VMX.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Microkernels implementing virtualization mechanisms are also referred to as *microhypervisor*.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Applying this terminology to Linux, KVM is a *hypervisor* and QEMU or Cloud Hypervisor are VMMs utilizing KVM as hypervisor.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] In his 1973 thesis *Architectural Principles for Virtual Computer Systems*, Robert P.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] These hypervisors run directly on the host's hardware to control the hardware and to manage guest operating systems.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] The first hypervisors, which IBM developed in the 1960s, were native hypervisors.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] These hypervisors run on a conventional operating system (OS) just as other computer programs do.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Type-2 hypervisors abstract guest operating systems from the host operating system, effectively creating an isolated system that can be interacted with by the host.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] The distinction between these two types is not always clear.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] For instance, KVM and bhyve are kernel modules that effectively convert the host operating system to a type-1 hypervisor.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] The first hypervisors providing full virtualization were the test tool SIMMON and the one-off IBM CP-40 research system, which began production use in January 1967 and became the first version of the IBM CP/CMS operating system.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] CP-40 ran on a S/360-40 modified at the Cambridge Scientific Center to support dynamic address translation, a feature that enabled virtualization.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Prior to this time, computer hardware had only been virtualized to the extent to allow multiple user applications to run concurrently, such as in CTSS and IBM M44/44X.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] With CP-40, the hardware's *supervisor state* was virtualized as well, allowing multiple operating systems to run concurrently in separate virtual machine contexts.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Programmers soon implemented CP-40 (as CP-67) for the IBM System/360-67, the first production computer system capable of full virtualization.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] IBM shipped this machine in 1966; it included page-translation-table hardware for virtual memory and other techniques that allowed a full virtualization of all kernel tasks, including I/O and interrupt handling.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] (The "official" operating system, the ill-fated TSS/360, did not employ full virtualization.) Both CP-40 and CP-67 began production use in 1967.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] CP/CMS was available to IBM customers from 1968 to early 1970s, in source code form without support.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] CP/CMS formed part of IBM's attempt to build robust time-sharing systems for its mainframe computers.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] By running multiple operating systems concurrently, the hypervisor increased system robustness and stability: Even if one operating system crashed, the others would continue working without interruption.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Indeed, this even allowed beta or experimental versions of operating systems‍—‌or even of new hardware‍—‌to be deployed and debugged, without jeopardizing the stable main production system, and without requiring costly additional development systems.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] IBM announced its System/370 series in 1970 without the virtual memory feature needed for virtualization, but added it in the August 1972 Advanced Function announcement.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Virtualization has been featured in all successor systems, such that all modern-day IBM mainframes, including the zSeries line, retain backward compatibility with the 1960s-era IBM S/360 line.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] The 1972 announcement also included VM/370, a reimplementation of CP/CMS for the S/370.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Unlike CP/CMS, IBM provided support for this version (though it was still distributed in source code form for several releases).
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] *VM* stands for *Virtual Machine*, emphasizing that all, not just some, of the hardware interfaces are virtualized.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Both VM and CP/CMS enjoyed early acceptance and rapid development by universities, corporate users, and time-sharing vendors, as well as within IBM.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Users played an active role in ongoing development, anticipating trends seen in modern open source projects.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] However, in a series of disputed and bitter battles, time-sharing lost out to batch processing through IBM political infighting, and VM remained IBM's "other" mainframe operating system for decades, losing to MVS.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] It enjoyed a resurgence of popularity and support from 2000 as the z/VM product, for example as the platform for Linux on IBM Z.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] As mentioned above, the VM control program includes a *hypervisor-call* handler that intercepts DIAG ("Diagnose", opcode x'83') instructions used within a virtual machine.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] This provides fast-path non-virtualized execution of file-system access and other operations (DIAG is a model-dependent privileged instruction, not used in normal programming, and thus is not virtualized.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] It is therefore available for use as a signal to the "host" operating system).
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] When first implemented in CP/CMS release 3.1, this use of DIAG provided an operating system interface that was analogous to the System/360 Supervisor Call instruction (SVC), but that did not require altering or extending the system's virtualization of SVC.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] In 1985 IBM introduced the PR/SM hypervisor to manage logical partitions (LPAR).
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Major Unix vendors, including HP, IBM, SGI, and Sun Microsystems, have been selling virtualized hardware since before 2000.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] These have generally been large, expensive systems (in the multimillion-dollar range at the high end), although virtualization has also been available on some low- and mid-range systems, such as IBM pSeries servers, HP Superdome series machines, and Sun/Oracle SPARC T series CoolThreads servers.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] IBM provides virtualization partition technology known as logical partitioning (LPAR) on System/390, zSeries, pSeries and IBM AS/400 systems.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] For IBM's Power Systems, the POWER Hypervisor (PHYP) is a native (bare-metal) hypervisor in firmware and provides isolation between LPARs.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Processor capacity is provided to LPARs in either a dedicated fashion or on an entitlement basis where unused capacity is harvested and can be re-allocated to busy workloads.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Groups of LPARs can have their processor capacity managed as if they were in a "pool" - IBM refers to this capability as Multiple Shared-Processor Pools (MSPPs) and implements it in servers with the POWER6 processor.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] LPAR and MSPP capacity allocations can be dynamically changed.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Memory is allocated to each LPAR (at LPAR initiation or dynamically) and is address-controlled by the POWER Hypervisor.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] For real-mode addressing by operating systems (AIX, Linux, IBM i), the Power processors (POWER4 onwards) have designed virtualization capabilities where a hardware address-offset is evaluated with the OS address-offset to arrive at the physical memory address.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Input/Output (I/O) adapters can be exclusively "owned" by LPARs or shared by LPARs through an appliance partition known as the Virtual I/O Server (VIOS).
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] HPE provides HP Integrity Virtual Machines (Integrity VM) to host multiple operating systems on their Itanium powered Integrity systems.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Itanium can run HP-UX, Linux, Windows and OpenVMS, and these environments are also supported as virtual servers on HP's Integrity VM platform.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] While it heavily leverages HP-UX, the Integrity VM hypervisor is really a hybrid that runs on bare-metal while guests are executing.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Running normal HP-UX applications on an Integrity VM host is heavily discouraged, because Integrity VM implements its own memory management, scheduling and I/O policies that are tuned for virtual machines and are not as effective for normal applications.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] HPE also provides more rigid partitioning of their Integrity and HP9000 systems by way of VPAR and nPar technology, the former offering shared resource partitioning and the latter offering complete I/O and processing isolation.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] The flexibility of virtual server environment (VSE) has given way to its use more frequently in newer deployments.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Wind River "Carrier Grade Linux" also runs on Sun's Hypervisor.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Full virtualization on SPARC processors proved straightforward: since its inception in the mid-1980s Sun deliberately kept the SPARC architecture clean of artifacts that would have impeded virtualization.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Similar trends have occurred with x86/x86-64 server platforms, where open-source projects such as Xen have led virtualization efforts.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] These include hypervisors built on Linux and Solaris kernels as well as custom kernels.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Since these technologies span from large systems down to desktops, they are described in the next section.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] x86 virtualization was introduced in the 1990s, with its emulation being included in Bochs.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Intel and AMD released their first x86 processors with hardware virtualisation in 2005 with Intel VT-x (code-named Vanderpool) and AMD-V (code-named Pacifica).
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] An alternative approach requires modifying the guest operating system to make a system call to the underlying hypervisor, rather than executing machine I/O instructions that the hypervisor simulates.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] This is called paravirtualization in Xen, a "hypercall" in Parallels Workstation, and a "DIAGNOSE code" in IBM VM.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Some microkernels, such as Mach and L4, are flexible enough to allow paravirtualization of guest operating systems.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Embedded hypervisors, targeting embedded systems and certain real-time operating system (RTOS) environments, are designed with different requirements when compared to desktop and enterprise systems, including robustness, security and real-time capabilities.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] The resource-constrained nature of multiple embedded systems, especially battery-powered mobile systems, imposes a further requirement for small memory-size and low overhead.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Finally, in contrast to the ubiquity of the x86 architecture in the PC world, the embedded world uses a wider variety of architectures and less standardized environments.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Support for virtualization requires memory protection (in the form of a memory management unit or at least a memory protection unit) and a distinction between user mode and privileged mode, which rules out most microcontrollers.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] This still leaves x86, MIPS, ARM and PowerPC as widely deployed architectures on medium- to high-end embedded systems.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] As manufacturers of embedded systems usually have the source code to their operating systems, they have less need for full virtualization in this space.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Instead, the performance advantages of paravirtualization make this usually the virtualization technology of choice.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Nevertheless, ARM and MIPS have recently added full virtualization support as an IP option and has included it in their latest high-end processors and architecture versions, such as ARM Cortex-A15 MPCore and ARMv8 EL2.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] Implementation of the concept has allegedly occurred in the SubVirt laboratory rootkit (developed jointly by Microsoft and University of Michigan researchers) as well as in the Blue Pill malware package.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] However, such assertions have been disputed by others who claim that it would be possible to detect the presence of a hypervisor-based rootkit.
[src:xen-hypervisor/hypervisor] In 2009, researchers from Microsoft and North Carolina State University demonstrated a hypervisor-layer anti-rootkit called Hooksafe that can provide generic protection against kernel-mode rootkits.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] In computing, **virtualization** (or **virtualisation** in Commonwealth English; see spelling differences,) abbreviated as **v12n**, is a series of technologies that allows dividing of physical computing resources into a series of virtual machines, operating systems, processes or containers.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Virtualization began in the 1960s with IBM CP/CMS.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] The control program CP provided each user with a simulated stand-alone System/360 computer.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] In hardware virtualization, the *host machine* is the machine that is used by the virtualization and the *guest machine* is the virtual machine.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] The words *host* and *guest* are used to distinguish the software that runs on the physical machine from the software that runs on the virtual machine.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] The software or firmware that creates a virtual machine on the host hardware is called a *hypervisor* or *virtual machine monitor*.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Hardware virtualization is not the same as hardware emulation.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Hardware-assisted virtualization facilitates building a virtual machine monitor and allows guest OSes to be run in isolation.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Desktop virtualization is the concept of separating the logical desktop from the physical machine.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Operating system-level virtualization, also known as containerization, refers to an operating system feature in which the kernel allows the existence of multiple isolated user-space instances.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] The usual goal of virtualization is to centralize administrative tasks while improving scalability and overall hardware-resource utilization.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] A form of virtualization was first demonstrated with IBM's CP-40 research system in 1967, then distributed via open source in CP/CMS in 1967–1972, and re-implemented in IBM's VM family from 1972 to the present.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Each CP/CMS user was provided a simulated, stand-alone computer.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Each such virtual machine had the complete capabilities of the underlying machine, and (for its user) the virtual machine was indistinguishable from a private system.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] This simulation was comprehensive, and was based on the *Principles of Operation* manual for the hardware.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] It thus included such elements as an instruction set, main memory, interrupts, exceptions, and device access.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] The result was a single machine that could be multiplexed among many users.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Hardware-assisted virtualization first appeared on the IBM System/370 in 1972, for use with VM/370, the first virtual machine operating system.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] IBM added virtual memory hardware to the System/370 series in 1972 which is not the same as Intel VT-x Rings providing a higher privilege level for Hypervisor to properly control Virtual Machines requiring full access to Supervisor and Program or User modes.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] With the increasing demand for high-definition computer graphics (e.g.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] CAD), virtualization of mainframes lost some attention in the late 1970s, when the upcoming minicomputers fostered resource allocation through distributed computing, encompassing the commoditization of microcomputers.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] The increase in compute capacity per x86 server (and in particular the substantial increase in modern networks' bandwidths) rekindled interest in data-center based computing which is based on virtualization techniques.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] The primary driver was the potential for server consolidation: virtualization allowed a single server to cost-efficiently consolidate compute power on multiple underutilized dedicated servers.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] The most visible hallmark of a return to the roots of computing is cloud computing, which is a synonym for data center based computing (or mainframe-like computing) through high bandwidth networks.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] It is closely connected to virtualization.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] This made it difficult to implement a virtual machine monitor for this type of processor.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Specific limitations included the inability to trap on some privileged instructions.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Therefore, to compensate for these architectural limitations, designers accomplished virtualization of the x86 architecture through two methods: **full virtualization** or **paravirtualization**.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Both create the illusion of physical hardware to achieve the goal of operating system independence from the hardware but present some trade-offs in performance and complexity.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Full virtualization was not fully available on the x86 platform prior to 2005.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Many platform hypervisors for the x86 platform came very close and claimed full virtualization (such as Adeos, Mac-on-Linux, Parallels Desktop for Mac, Parallels Workstation, VMware Workstation, VMware Server (formerly GSX Server), VirtualBox, Win4BSD, and Win4Lin Pro).
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] In 2005 and 2006, Intel and AMD (working independently) created new processor extensions to the x86 architecture called Intel VT-x and AMD-V, respectively.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] On the Itanium architecture, hardware-assisted virtualization is known as VT-i.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Software executed on these virtual machines is separated from the underlying hardware resources.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] For example, a computer that is running Arch Linux may host a virtual machine that looks like a computer with the Microsoft Windows operating system; Windows-based software can be run on the virtual machine.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Full virtualization employs techniques that pools physical computer resources into one or more instances; each running a virtual environment where any software or operating system capable of execution on the raw hardware can be run in the virtual machine.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Two common full virtualization techniques are typically used: (a) binary translation and (b) hardware-assisted full virtualization.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Binary translation automatically modifies the software on-the-fly to replace instructions that "pierce the virtual machine" with a different, virtual machine safe sequence of instructions.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Hardware-assisted virtualization allows guest operating systems to be run in isolation with virtually no modification to the (guest) operating system.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] This approach was pioneered in 1966 with the IBM CP-40 and CP-67, predecessors of the VM family.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Some hypervisors perform binary translation between guest and host, either between differing instruction set architectures or between a guest and host using the same instruction set.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] The hypervisor may be designed to interpret a guest's machine code directly or generate machine code for the host's architecture in a form of dynamic binary translation.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Most common hypervisors, including ones that use hardware to assist virtualization, perform binary translation of some instructions relating to hardware access.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] In such a case, the hypervisor will trap the instruction and perform the functions to emulate the required devices.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Hypervisors that perform binary translation may also be designed to substitute instructions within the guest context to aid security or performance.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Hardware-assisted virtualization (or *accelerated virtualization; Xen calls it hardware virtual machine (HVM), and Virtual Iron calls it native virtualization)* is a way of improving overall efficiency of hardware virtualization using help from the host processors.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] A full virtualization is used to emulate a complete hardware environment, or virtual machine, in which an unmodified guest operating system (using the same instruction set as the host machine) effectively executes in complete isolation.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Hardware-assisted virtualization was first introduced on the IBM 308X processors in 1980, with the Start Interpretive Execution (SIE) instruction.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] It was added to x86 processors (Intel VT-x, AMD-V or VIA VT) in 2005, 2006 and 2010 respectively.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] IBM offers hardware virtualization for its IBM Power Systems hardware for AIX, Linux and IBM i, and for its IBM Z mainframes.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] IBM refers to its specific form of hardware virtualization as "logical partition", or more commonly as LPAR.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Hardware-assisted virtualization reduces the maintenance overhead of binary translation based virtualization as it reduces (ideally, eliminates) the code that needs to be translated in the guest operating system.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] It is also considerably easier to obtain better performance.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Paravirtualization is a virtualization technique that presents a software interface to the virtual machines which is similar, yet not identical, to the underlying hardware–software interface.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Paravirtualization improves performance and efficiency, compared to full virtualization, by having the guest operating system communicate with the hypervisor.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] By allowing the guest operating system to indicate its intent to the hypervisor, each can cooperate to obtain better performance when running in a virtual machine.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] The intent of the modified interface is to reduce the portion of the guest's execution time spent performing operations which are substantially more difficult to run in a virtual environment compared to a non-virtualized environment.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] The paravirtualization provides specially defined 'hooks' to allow the guest(s) and host to request and acknowledge these tasks, which would otherwise be executed in the virtual domain (where execution performance is worse).
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] A successful paravirtualized platform may allow the virtual machine monitor (VMM) to be simpler (by relocating execution of critical tasks from the virtual domain to the host domain), and/or reduce the overall performance degradation of machine execution inside the virtual guest.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Paravirtualization requires the guest operating system to be explicitly ported for the para-API – a conventional OS distribution that is not paravirtualization-aware can still run on a paravirtualizing VMM.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] However, even in cases where the operating system cannot be modified, components may be available that enable many of the significant performance advantages of paravirtualization.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] For example, the Xen Windows GPLPV project provides a kit of paravirtualization-aware device drivers, that are intended to be installed into a Microsoft Windows virtual guest running on the Xen hypervisor.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Such applications tend to be accessible through the paravirtual machine interface environment.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] This ensures run-mode compatibility across multiple encryption algorithm models, allowing seamless integration within the paravirtual framework.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] The term "paravirtualization" was first used in the research literature in association with the Denali Virtual Machine Manager.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] The term is also used to describe the Xen, L4, TRANGO, VMware, Wind River and XtratuM hypervisors.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] All these projects use or can use paravirtualization techniques to support high performance virtual machines on x86 hardware by implementing a virtual machine that does not implement the hard-to-virtualize parts of the actual x86 instruction set.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] In 2005, VMware proposed a paravirtualization interface, the Virtual Machine Interface (VMI), as a communication mechanism between the guest operating system and the hypervisor.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] This interface enabled transparent paravirtualization in which a single binary version of the operating system can run either on native hardware or on a hypervisor in paravirtualized mode.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] The first appearance of paravirtualization support in Linux occurred with the merge of the ppc64 port in 2002, which supported running Linux as a paravirtualized guest on IBM pSeries (RS/6000) and iSeries (AS/400) hardware.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] At the USENIX conference in 2006 in Boston, Massachusetts, a number of Linux development vendors (including IBM, VMware, Xen, and Red Hat) collaborated on an alternative form of paravirtualization, initially developed by the Xen group, called "paravirt-ops".
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] The paravirt-ops code (often shortened to pv-ops) was included in the mainline Linux kernel as of the 2.6.23 version, and provides a hypervisor-agnostic interface between the hypervisor and guest kernels.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Distribution support for pv-ops guest kernels appeared starting with Ubuntu 7.04 and RedHat 9.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Xen hypervisors based on any 2.6.24 or later kernel support pv-ops guests, as does VMware's Workstation product beginning with version 6.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Hybrid virtualization combines full virtualization techniques with paravirtualized drivers to overcome limitations with hardware-assisted full virtualization.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] A hardware-assisted full virtualization approach uses an unmodified guest operating system that involves many VM traps producing high CPU overheads limiting scalability and the efficiency of server consolidation.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] The hybrid virtualization approach overcomes this problem.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Desktop virtualization separates the logical desktop from the physical machine.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] One form of desktop virtualization, virtual desktop infrastructure (VDI), can be thought of as a more advanced form of hardware virtualization.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Rather than interacting with a host computer directly via a keyboard, mouse, and monitor, the user interacts with the host computer using another desktop computer or a mobile device by means of a network connection, such as a LAN, Wireless LAN or even the Internet.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] In addition, the host computer in this scenario becomes a server computer capable of hosting multiple virtual machines at the same time for multiple users.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Companies like HP and IBM provide a hybrid VDI model with a range of virtualization software and delivery models to improve upon the limitations of distributed client computing.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Selected client environments move workloads from PCs and other devices to data center servers, creating well-managed virtual clients, with applications and client operating environments hosted on servers and storage in the data center.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] For users, this means they can access their desktop from any location, without being tied to a single client device.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Since the resources are centralized, users moving between work locations can still access the same client environment with their applications and data.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] For IT administrators, this means a more centralized, efficient client environment that is easier to maintain and able to more quickly respond to the changing needs of the user and business.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Another form, session virtualization, allows multiple users to connect and log into a shared but powerful computer over the network and use it simultaneously.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Each is given a desktop and a personal folder in which they store their files.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] With multiseat configuration, session virtualization can be accomplished using a single PC with multiple monitors, keyboards, and mice connected.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Thin clients, which are seen in desktop virtualization, are simple and/or cheap computers that are primarily designed to connect to the network.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] They may lack significant hard disk storage space, RAM or even processing power, but many organizations are beginning to look at the cost benefits of eliminating "thick client" desktops that are packed with software (and require software licensing fees) and making more strategic investments.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Desktop virtualization simplifies software versioning and patch management, where the new image is simply updated on the server, and the desktop gets the updated version when it reboots.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] It also enables centralized control over what applications the user is allowed to have access to on the workstation.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Moving virtualized desktops into the cloud creates hosted virtual desktops (HVDs), in which the desktop images are centrally managed and maintained by a specialist hosting firm.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Benefits include scalability and the reduction of capital expenditure, which is replaced by a monthly operational cost.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Such instances, called containers, partitions, virtual environments (VEs) or jails (FreeBSD jail or chroot jail), may look like (physical) computers from the point of view of programs running in them.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] A computer program running on an ordinary operating system can see all resources (connected devices, files and folders, network shares, CPU power, quantifiable hardware capabilities) of that computer.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] However, programs running inside a container can only see the container's contents and devices assigned to the container.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] This provides many of the benefits that virtual machines have such as standardization and scalability, while using less resources as the kernel is shared between containers.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Containerization started gaining prominence in 2014, with the introduction of Docker.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] A common goal of virtualization is to centralize administrative tasks while improving scalability and overall hardware-resource utilization.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] With virtualization, several operating systems can be run in parallel on a single central processing unit (CPU).
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] This parallelism tends to reduce overhead costs and differs from multitasking, which involves running several programs on the same OS.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Using virtualization, an enterprise can better manage updates and rapid changes to the operating system and applications without disrupting the user.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Ultimately, virtualization dramatically improves the efficiency and availability of resources and applications in an organization.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Instead of relying on the old model of "one server, one application" that leads to underutilized resources, virtual resources are dynamically applied to meet business needs without any excess fat".
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] Virtual machines running proprietary operating systems require licensing, regardless of the host machine's operating system.
[src:xen-hypervisor/paravirtualization] For example, installing Microsoft Windows into a VM guest requires its licensing requirements to be satisfied.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] The Xen Project community develops and maintains Xen Project as free and open-source software, subject to the requirements of the GNU General Public License (GPL), version 2.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Xen Project is currently available for the IA-32, x86-64 and ARM instruction sets.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Xen Project runs in a more privileged CPU state than any other software on the machine, except for firmware.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Responsibilities of the hypervisor include memory management and CPU scheduling of all virtual machines ("domains"), and for launching the most privileged domain ("dom0") - the only virtual machine which by default has direct access to hardware.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] From the dom0 the hypervisor can be managed and unprivileged domains ("domU") can be launched.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] The dom0 domain is typically a version of Linux or BSD.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Xen Project boots from a bootloader such as GNU GRUB, and then usually loads a paravirtualized host operating system into the host domain (dom0).
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Xen originated as a research project at the University of Cambridge led by Ian Pratt, a senior lecturer in the Computer Laboratory, and his PhD student Keir Fraser.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] According to Anil Madhavapeddy, an early contributor, Xen started as a bet on whether Fraser could make multiple Linux Kernels boot on the same hardware in a weekend.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] The first public release of Xen was made in 2003, with v1.0 following in 2004.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Soon after, Pratt and Fraser along with other Cambridge alumni including Simon Crosby and founding CEO Nick Gault created XenSource Inc. to turn Xen into a competitive enterprise product.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] To support embedded systems such as smartphone/ IoT with relatively scarce hardware computing resources, the Secure Xen ARM architecture on an ARM CPU was exhibited at Xen Summit on April 17, 2007, held in IBM TJ Watson.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] The first public release of Secure Xen ARM source code was made at Xen Summit on June 24, 2008 by Sang-bum Suh, a Cambridge alumnus, in Samsung Electronics.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] On October 22, 2007, Citrix Systems completed its acquisition of XenSource, and the Xen Project moved to the xen.org domain.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] This move had started some time previously, and made public the existence of the Xen Project Advisory Board (Xen AB), which had members from Citrix, IBM, Intel, Hewlett-Packard, Novell, Red Hat, Sun Microsystems and Oracle.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] The Xen Advisory Board advises the Xen Project leader and is responsible for the Xen trademark, which Citrix has freely licensed to all vendors and projects that implement the Xen hypervisor.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Citrix also used the Xen brand itself for some proprietary products unrelated to Xen, including XenApp and XenDesktop.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] On April 15, 2013, it was announced that the Xen Project was moved under the auspices of the Linux Foundation as a Collaborative Project.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] The Linux Foundation launched a new trademark for "Xen Project" to differentiate the project from any commercial use of the older "Xen" trademark.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] A new community website was launched at xenproject.org as part of the transfer.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Project members at the time of the announcement included: Amazon, AMD, Bromium, CA Technologies, Calxeda, Cisco, Citrix, Google, Intel, Oracle, Samsung, and Verizon.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] The Xen project itself is self-governing.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Since version 3.0 of the Linux kernel, Xen support for dom0 and domU exists in the mainline kernel.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Internet hosting service companies use hypervisors to provide virtual private servers.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Amazon EC2 (from August 2006 to November 2017), IBM SoftLayer, Liquid Web, Fujitsu Global Cloud Platform, Linode, OrionVM and Rackspace Cloud use Xen as the primary VM hypervisor for their product offerings.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Virtual machine monitors (also known as hypervisors) also often operate on mainframes and large servers running IBM, HP, and other systems.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Xen's support for virtual machine live migration from one host to another allows load balancing and the avoidance of downtime.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Virtualization also has benefits when working on development (including the development of operating systems): running the new system as a guest avoids the need to reboot the physical computer whenever a bug occurs.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Sandboxed guest systems can also help in computer-security research, allowing study of the effects of some virus or worm without the possibility of compromising the host system.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Finally, hardware appliance vendors may decide to ship their appliance running several guest systems, so as to be able to execute various pieces of software that require different operating systems.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Xen provides a form of virtualization known as paravirtualization, in which guests run a modified operating system.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] The guests are modified to use a special hypercall ABI, instead of certain architectural features.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Through paravirtualization, Xen can achieve high performance even on its host architecture (x86) which has a reputation for non-cooperation with traditional virtualization techniques.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Xen can run paravirtualized guests ("PV guests" in Xen terminology) even on CPUs without any explicit support for virtualization.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Paravirtualization avoids the need to emulate a full set of hardware and firmware services, which makes a PV system simpler to manage and reduces the attack surface exposed to potentially malicious guests.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] On 32-bit x86, the Xen host kernel code runs in Ring 0, while the hosted domains run in *Ring 1* (kernel) and *Ring 3* (applications).
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] CPUs that support virtualization make it possible to run unmodified guests, including proprietary operating systems (such as Microsoft Windows).
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] This is known as hardware-assisted virtualization, however, in Xen this is known as hardware virtual machine (HVM).
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Both Intel and AMD have contributed modifications to Xen to exploit their respective Intel VT-x and AMD-V architecture extensions.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Use of ARM v7A and v8A virtualization extensions came with Xen 4.3.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] HVM extensions also often offer new instructions to allow direct calls by a paravirtualized guest/driver into the hypervisor, typically used for I/O or other operations needing high performance.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] These allow HVM guests with suitable minor modifications to gain many of the performance benefits of paravirtualized I/O.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] In current versions of Xen (up to 4.2) only fully virtualized HVM guests can make use of hardware facilities for multiple independent levels of memory protection and paging.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] As a result, for some workloads, HVM guests with PV drivers (also known as PV-on-HVM, or PVH) provide better performance than pure PV guests.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Xen HVM has device emulation based on the QEMU project to provide I/O virtualization to the virtual machines.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] The system emulates hardware via a patched QEMU "device manager" (qemu-dm) daemon running as a backend in dom0.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] This means that the virtualized machines see an emulated version of a fairly basic PC.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] In a performance-critical environment, PV-on-HVM disk and network drivers are used during the normal guest operation, so that the emulated PC hardware is mostly used for booting.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Administrators can "live migrate" Xen virtual machines between physical hosts across a LAN without loss of availability.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] During this procedure, the LAN iteratively copies the memory of the virtual machine to the destination without stopping its execution.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] The process requires a stoppage of around 60–300 ms to perform final synchronization before the virtual machine begins executing at its final destination, providing an illusion of seamless migration.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Similar technology can serve to suspend running virtual machines to disk, "freezing" their running state for resumption at a later date.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Xen can scale to 4095 physical CPUs, 256 VCPUs per HVM guest, 512 VCPUs per PV guest, 16 TB of RAM per host, and up to 1 TB of RAM per HVM guest or 512 GB of RAM per PV guest.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Xen implements shared memory using *grant tables*, which allow domains to specify memory pages to share with other selected domains.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Xen can be shipped in a dedicated virtualization platform, such as XCP-ng or XenServer (formerly Citrix Hypervisor, and before that Citrix XenServer, and before that XenSource's XenEnterprise).
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Alternatively, Xen is distributed as an optional configuration of many standard operating systems.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Guest systems can run fully virtualized (which requires hardware support), paravirtualized (which requires a modified guest operating system), or fully virtualized with paravirtualized drivers (PVHVM).
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Most operating systems which can run on PCs can run as a Xen HVM guest.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Xen version 3.0 introduced the capability to run Microsoft Windows as a guest operating system unmodified if the host machine's processor supports hardware virtualization provided by Intel VT-x (formerly codenamed Vanderpool) or AMD-V (formerly codenamed Pacifica).
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] During the development of Xen 1.x, Microsoft Research, along with the University of Cambridge Operating System group, developed a port of Windows XP to Xen — made possible by Microsoft's Academic Licensing Program.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] The terms of this license do not allow the publication of this port, although documentation of the experience appears in the original Xen SOSP paper.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] James Harper and the Xen open-source community have started developing free software paravirtualization drivers for Windows.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] These provide front-end drivers for the Xen block and network devices and allow much higher disk and network performance for Windows systems running in HVM mode.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Without these drivers all disk and network traffic has to be processed through QEMU-DM.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Subsequently, Citrix has released under a BSD license (and continues to maintain) PV drivers for Windows.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] Third-party developers have built a number of tools (known as Xen Management Consoles) to facilitate the common tasks of administering a Xen host, such as configuring, starting, monitoring and stopping of Xen guests.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] The Xen hypervisor is covered by the GNU General Public Licence, so all of these versions contain a core of free software with source code.
[src:xen-hypervisor/xen] However, many of them contain proprietary additions.
